It‚Äôs called growth, dahling! Ever heard of it?

#grombre

I started getting silver / grey hairs around 15 years old. I‚Äôve been dying my hair since I was 22 because I literally thought I had no other option. Grey equalled old to me - something most women are told is a bad, bad thing. Anything that symbolised this simply HAD to be covered! Anyway, recently I‚Äôve felt differently. I want to be my natural hair colour. If silver hair really = being old then people in their teens, twenties and thirties wouldn‚Äôt get them. Evolution-wise I think it‚Äôs more likely to just signal being an adult...
‚Å£
Anyway, this post is a) for my own self-encouragement üíÖüèº b) for the encouragement of others dealing with the same beauty industry BS c) to give you all a heads up that if I have crazy roots for a while, this is why üòÇ I hope to make it some kind of balayage-highlight-whatever at some point to help it grow out less crazily. But really I‚Äôm just looking forward to being my natural colour. ‚Å£
‚Å£
As a side note - what kick-started this decision were  the headaches and feeling of sickness I got from dyes. I used organic dye and I found out it was still filled with carcinogenic chemicals. I‚Äôm not putting my body through that for anything. ‚Å£‚Å£

Thanks to these hashtags for the inspo: so many young women making this change and I‚Äôm full of admiration. #SilverSisters #grombre
